04323nam a22006735i 9780292743830DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212013txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927438307 a10.7560/7438232doi  a(DE-B1597)587817  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aHQ1236.5.C5 -- A33 2013eb 7aART0440002bisacsh04a305.409831 aAdams, Jacqueline, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aArt Against Dictatorship :bMaking and Exporting Arpilleras Under Pinochet /cJacqueline Adams. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2013  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Solidarity Art -- t2 Beginnings Unemployment and Joining Groups -- t3 The First Arpillera Groups -- t4 Arpillera Making in Other Groups and Its Spread -- t5 Producing the Arpilleras -- t6 Selling Arpilleras -- t7 The Buyers Abroad -- t8 Selling, Giving, and Exhibiting Arpilleras in Chile -- t9 The Consequences of Arpillera Making -- t10 Conclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aArt can be a powerful avenue of resistance to oppressive governments. During the dictatorship of Augusto Pinochet in Chile, some of the country’s least powerful citizens—impoverished women living in Santiago’s shantytowns—spotlighted the government’s failings and use of violence by creating and selling arpilleras, appliquéd pictures in cloth that portrayed the unemployment, poverty, and repression that they endured, their work to make ends meet, and their varied forms of protest. Smuggled out of Chile by human rights organizations, the arpilleras raised international awareness of the Pinochet regime’s abuses while providing income for the arpillera makers and creating a network of solidarity between the people of Chile and sympathizers throughout the world. Using the Chilean arpilleras as a case study, this book explores how dissident art can be produced under dictatorship, when freedom of expression is absent and repression rife, and the consequences of its production for the resistance and for the artists. Taking a sociological approach based on interviews, participant observation, archival research, and analysis of a visual database, Jacqueline Adams examines the emergence of the arpilleras and then traces their journey from the workshops and homes in which they were made, to the human rights organizations that exported them, and on to sellers and buyers abroad, as well as in Chile. She then presents the perspectives of the arpillera makers and human rights organization staff, who discuss how the arpilleras strengthened the resistance and empowered the women who made them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aArpilleras. 0aDecorative artsxPolitical aspectszChilexHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzChilexHistoryy20th century. 7aART / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292743830423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292743830/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK